<div id="python-in-r-markdown" class="section level2">
<h2>Python in R Markdown</h2>
<p>The following is a short guide for using Python in R Markdown using the <code>reticulate</code> package and the <code>use_python()</code> command. This assumes that you do not have Python installed (or at least Python 3) yet.</p>
<p>Before we begin, go over following steps:</p>
<ul>
<li>Download the <a href="https://docs.conda.io/en/latest/miniconda.html">miniconda</a> Python distribution</li>
<li>Install the <code>reticulate</code> package in R</li>
<li>Find the folder (in your computer) where you installed <code>miniconda3</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Now let’s load <code>reticulate</code> and find the version of Python we want to use. Then we load the Python interpreter for our R session.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#Load the reticulate package
library(reticulate)
#Find the miniconda3
use_python(&quot;C:/Users/alhdz/miniconda3&quot;, required = T)
#Load the Python shell
repl_python()</code></pre>
<p>Let’s check which version of python we are using.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#Inspect the Python version
py_config()</code></pre>
<pre><code>## python:         C:/Users/alhdz/miniconda3/python.exe
## libpython:      C:/Users/alhdz/miniconda3/python39.dll
## pythonhome:     C:/Users/alhdz/miniconda3
## version:        3.9.1 (default, Dec 11 2020, 09:29:25) [MSC v.1916 64 bit (AMD64)]
## Architecture:   64bit
## numpy:          C:/Users/alhdz/miniconda3/Lib/site-packages/numpy
## numpy_version:  1.19.2
## sys:            [builtin module]
## 
## NOTE: Python version was forced by use_python function</code></pre>
<p>To run Python code, chunks should be named <em>python</em> rather than <em>r</em>. You can use the <strong>Insert</strong> option in the top right corner of the RStudio <em>editor window</em> and select the <code>Python</code> option. It is important to remember that objects that are loaded into the Python environment will not show up in your RStudio <em>environment window</em>. Similarly, if you type <code>repl_python()</code> in your console, you will notice that when it expecting Python code, you will see <code>&gt;&gt;&gt;</code> rather than <code>&gt;</code>, you can go back to R by typing <code>exit</code>.</p>
<p>Let’s make an example. If you try the syntax below in an <code>r</code> chunk, it will not run! In a <code>python</code> chunk however:</p>
<pre class="python"><code>a=&quot;Hello&quot;+&quot; World&quot;
print(a)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Hello World</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-libraries" class="section level2">
<h2>Python Libraries</h2>
<p>Now let’s install some libraries for Python, these are like packages in R. Let’s run the <strong>Anaconda Prompt (miniconda3)</strong> and type <code>conda install seaborn</code> then write <code>pip install -U scikit-learn</code> to install scikit-learn. The former is a data visualization library (similar to <code>ggplot2</code>) and the latter a machine learning library.</p>
<p>Now, let’s load the libraries we just installed. We can use R syntax in an <code>r</code> chunk, for example:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sklearn &lt;- import(&#39;sklearn&#39;)
sklearn</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Module(sklearn)</code></pre>
<p>We also can use the Python syntax in a <code>python</code> chunk. Let’s do some troubleshooting that is common for Markdown Python plots in Windows.</p>
<pre class="python"><code>#Sometimes R Markdown has trouble finding some plotting plugins! 
import os
os.environ[&#39;QT_QPA_PLATFORM_PLUGIN_PATH&#39;] = &#39;C:/Users/alhdz/miniconda3/Library/plugins/platforms&#39;</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="penguins-with-seaborn" class="section level2">
<h2>Penguins with <code>seaborn</code></h2>
<p>Now lets <code>import</code> seaborn using Python syntax and use the Palmer Penguins data set to make a histogram.</p>
<pre class="python"><code>import seaborn as sns
df = sns.load_dataset(&quot;penguins&quot;)
sns.histplot(data=df, x=&quot;flipper_length_mm&quot;, hue=&quot;species&quot;, multiple=&quot;stack&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="penguins-with-ggplot2" class="section level2">
<h2>Penguins with <code>ggplot2</code></h2>
<p>Finally, let’s do the same thing, but this time with <code>ggplot2</code> and R syntax.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>library(palmerpenguins) #you may need to install!
library(tidyverse)
df &lt;- data.frame(penguins)

df %&gt;% 
    ggplot(aes(x=flipper_length_mm, fill=species)) +
    geom_histogram(color=&quot;black&quot;, bins = 10)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
